Kiu Ghesik wrote:
Regardless, since this isn't the IDT, allow me to present another cliché: humans. Show me a nation of squids and I'll be happy. We have Bears Armed, a nation of bears, and I've seen a nation of cats, but what about sea creatures? Sharks? Dolphins? Whales?

nonhuman nations are indeed pretty based
that is, when they don't fall into "this is exactly like a human nation but the population isn't human"
more diversity of thought to reflect diversity of biology, pls :pleading_face:


I want to build Versilia’s social and political structures based on the hivemindedness of the “elves”/vampires, as they have a natural psychic link with other members of their species. It’s an extrasensory empathy, allowing them to feel one another’s emotions, drives and the sort, boosting their cooperative capabilities to levels which humans themselves cannot achieve.

As well, the caste system and caste based dimorphism that’s present within the species would heavily affect social structure, and that’s pretty core to Versilia.

However, Versilia has a large human minority or plurality that doesn’t have this psychic link, nor the expanded means of communication that vampires have (including pheromones, greater range of sounds, greater range of body language and social cues that’s also different between castes, and so on in extension to human means of communication); this will strongly affect life in Versilia and its overall structure.

Savroyska wrote:I’d like to see an alternatively evolved english though


That’s essentially what I’m planning for the Britain in Versilia’s TL. English has taken a different path than OTL, resembling Dutch in a number of ways; I currently plan for the language to have its 3 gender system and the remnants of a case system but not a full one like German. Its orthography has also changed with German printing presses and reforms of spelling, such as the ‘hard’ {c} becoming {k} in all instances, the diphthong {ch} remaining spelt as {c}, the ‘soft’ {c} never coming into use and instead {s} is used. The ending {d} on most words devoiced and became {t}, so ‘land’ became lant. Affixes like ‘-ing’ standardised into -ung, and ‘be-’ remained in common use; words like bewerung, meaning ‘defence’, alongside bestirung/bestyrung (‘movement’) and more. The name of Britain in Versilia’s TL is Keningrik Briten(lant).
